article.headline: Huskies' 17-2 run puts game out of reach
article.linkText: UConn beats Florida State to extend winning streak to 50 games
article.story:
TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Connecticut  coach Geno Auriemma doesn't
care a whole lot about records -- just continuing success.

	   And the Huskies (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) had more of that Monday night when
Diana Taurasi and Ann Strother scored 18 points apiece to extend
the nation's longest winning streak to 50 games with a 74-55
victory over Florida State.

	   "I think the streaks in March are the ones that matter,"
Auriemma said. "I don't think this streak has any great
significance as far as our program goes."

	   The Huskies (11-0) didn't start out well. They committed 11
turnovers, and even trailed the Seminoles for a 4-minute stretch in
the first half.

	   Tasheika Morris scored 18 to lead Florida State (7-3), which
stayed competitive for much of the first half before UConn's trap
defense forced a series of turnovers.

	   "We just go into every game thinking we're going to play
certain defenses regardless," Auriemma said. "When we did trap
them I thought it would get us going a little. I thought the game
was pretty much decided there in the last five, six minutes of the
first half."

	   The Huskies responded to a 17-13 deficit with a 17-2 run.
Strother made two free throws to tie it at 17, and Taurasi followed
with a layup to put the Huskies ahead for good.

	   "They put the trap on and we turned the ball over four out of
five possessions," Seminoles coach Sue Semrau said. "And I
thought that was the turning point of the game."

	   Maria Conlon made a 3-pointer to extend the lead to nine with
4:44 left in the first half, and followed with a layup 38 seconds
later to stretch it to 30-19. The Huskies were ahead 39-26 at
halftime.

	   Florida State took its lead on Holly Johnson's free throw with
12:09 to play in the first half. The Seminoles extended their
advantage to 17-13 when Katelyn Vujas hit another free throw.

	   "Forget that we were shooting poorly," Auriemma said. "We
were just playing horrible basketball that first 10 minutes."
